## Risk Register

| Risk | Why it matters | Mitigation | Kill / pivot criterion |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Overclaiming science capability | The mission is frontier-scale, but market trust dies if claims outrun evidence | Use claim ladders, `UNVERIFIABLE`, source-backed statements, and bounded demos | If the demo requires claiming discovery rather than evidence handling, narrow the demo |
| Crowded AI observability market | Buyers already see many tools | Position after observability; consume traces instead of replacing stacks | If buyers say trace exports already satisfy action accountability, focus on Build/visual wedge |
| BuildLang maturity mismatch | Language ambition may exceed current ecosystem adoption | Lead with receipts and proof demos, not replacement claims | If receipts cannot be generated/replayed reliably, postpone external language positioning |
| Color/display mutation risk | Calibration tools can affect real workstation state | Keep first packet read-only; never apply LUT/ICC/DDC changes in public demo | If a demo needs mutation, require restore receipts and local-only gating first |
| Research credibility gap | Labs will reject vague "AI scientist" framing | Start with formal proof packets and failure-preserving evidence | If formal checker bridge is too slow, ship source/proof-attempt packet with explicit manual-review status |
| Schema sprawl | Too many packet types can fragment the platform | Keep one proof packet envelope with domain adapters | If every demo needs incompatible schemas, stop and define the envelope first |
| Distribution confusion | A megatool can look like a pile of tools | Brand product families by buyer problem, not repo names | If users cannot explain the product after one demo, simplify to one receipt story |

